      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "What does this imply about coordination geometry?\n- The relatively large first four stepwise constants indicate strong binding up to four NH3 ligands, consistent with Cu(II) filling an equatorial set to form [Cu(NH3)4]2+. This aligns with Cu(II)’s common tetragonally distorted (Jahn–Teller) octahedral preference, where four equatorial bonds are strong and any axial additions (n > 4) would be much weaker. In practice, the monotonic but still sizable K4 supports a 4‑coordinate equatorial core (square‑planar/tetragonal) as the dominant motif in aqueous ammonia.",
